task.summary: Default task

Initial lightly tested call implementation using amr narrow band library. Does not crash at the end of calls and is 12.2kbit/s. Mic mute/unmute changed from smartly making sure only 1 media encoder thread is running and patiently waiting until it's your turn to start the media encoder if there is a lineup to a simple 2 boolean system with sleep in while no-op loop. Much simpler, way less moving parts. Put a warning about mic mute/unmute 1 second lag.

Move encode/decode thread call to onStop() in the try because in cases of socket crap out, both will try to call onStop(). The first one that calls onStop() will kill the main ui thread. Everything will be fine. The second one that calls onStop() will have some kind of null error because the ui thread is gone and onStop() lives in the ui thread. No need for some elaborate "alreadyCalledStop" or "didCallStop" boolean voodoo. Just catch the bad attempt. Simple and effective.

Simplify Logging System, Make SQLite Singleton
Make Utils.logcat also record to the database logs if Vars.SHOUDLOG is set. No need to write code to log once to the console and once to the database. Use online suggestion of singleton sqlite to prevent leaks and make it easier to access sqlite from Utils static functions.
Rearrange log summary to see date and time by removing message preview. Show day of the week in log details.
Don't draw all the logs in the ui table. Takes too long if there are a lot. Instead just add a more button to load more.
Give proper error message if socket read thinks it's the end of file when it really isn't.
Rearrange xml to make it more inline with the actual layout. Remove warned about stuff.

More call improvements
Use buffered output to send voice in kilobyte packets instead of 32byte packets. Each packet has ~40bytes of header. Don't waste data making a 40 byte header for each 32 byte chunk. More of the data is header than voice! 1kb ~ 2/3 of a second.
Move encoder/decoder thread tags to their own inner classes. Fix copy and paste tag mistake.
About this app screen
Properly stringify menu labels because you can see them when long clicking them

Call history feature
Fix call history logging to use time stamp in milliseconds, not seconds. Fix call incoming timer task. Since it will only run once, use the initial run delay and then give an arbitrary short period to give it time to get killed. Make the call history aware of missed calls. Add images for incoming/outgoing/missed in call history (png images match the new material colors) Relieve command listener of keeping track of history. Get rid of recent history and just make it all history. UI will handle "paginating" call history, not db.

Settings Feature
Changed ports to save as string as anything that will be changed on a proper android preference fragment must be a string. Added file creation dates to about and history.

Improve Settings
Validate command and media port numbers to make sure they're in the port range. Make a placeholder for the settings fragment to be loaded into so the action bar shows up.
Fix erroneous call end asyncs being sent and write down why it happened.
Fix call audio using 5X the data and coming out in super slow motion audio. (I assumed the amr library would down convert 44100 sample rate to 8000 but it didn't)
Don't send garbage data during a call just to see if the connections are still good... of course they are: you're in the call. Garbage data may interfere with amr decoding.

Allow a 1 second delay between sending the call end command and killing the socket. Otherwise the socket might be killed before the command makes it to the server. The other person will not know you ended the call and get the silent treatment.
Double check the contact list is there. In case it got killed for ??memory saving purposes?? redraw the contact list.

Actually play a ringtone or vibrate on incoming calls depending on whether in vibrate or normal mode. If in dead silent mode, do nothing. (Respect dead silent)
Move the call timeout length to its own constant in Const. Avoid 2 variables that do the same thing which is just asking for bugs.
Remove accidental manifest junk.
Switch from string comparison to int comparison for performance (even if just a bit).

Don't allow orientation changes for voice call screen. Causes extreme stuttering in call audio because orientation changes causes the screen to be redrawn. The original background threads to send/receive call data are still going. Also no value in the landscape orientation for this screen.
Don't allow orientation changes. Causes a crash because of the ringtone and vibrator object recreation while the old ones were still active.
Fix random delay of call incoming screen crashing after rejecting a call. Cleanup its timer for rejects too.

Use the jbyte to reestablish the media socket. Otherwise the initial "1" in the timestamp is missing which will make it way off. Attempt to fix endless connection die/retry that radomly happens by putting a 1 second delay and making sure the old sockets are good and dead before continuing. Remove useless vars.cmdlistenerrunning.
Add missing really quit dialog.

Adjust media output bufferisze to half a kb. Produces ~1 second lag. Increases data usage from 4kb/s --> 5kb/s.
Put in a work around for audio recorder not being able to initialize. ??maybe?? works????? (doesn't happen very often)

Drop audio that comes in too fast on the assumption its the back log from a bad connection. Totally ruins real time-ish call audio.
Maximum network rate for audio download from ~2700 samples of server input /2 (because there were 2 devices)

Drop audio that comes in too fast on the assumption its the back log from a bad connection. Totally ruins real time-ish call audio.
Maximum network rate for audio download from ~2700 samples of server input /2 (because there were 2 devices)
When the microphone can't be initialized, do something with that known failure and end the call. Don't pretend like everything's ok.
Log to the db when the microphone coulnd't initialize.

Final solution for java socket stupidities of not connect<-->disconenct many times a second. Detect if the last dead command socket was sent very recently. If this happens 10 times, kill itself and reschedule itself to start after 5 seconds. (5 seconds is assumed to be enough to quit)
Adjust proximity sensor threshold for "close to face" for the I9000.

Redo ongoing notification.
Include a background color if the cell phone supports it. Change the notification as soon as there is a state change. Don't wait for the screen to change.
When cleaning up the AudioRecord and AudioTrack, there may be a race condition if the CallMain ui exits first.
Don't show the progress dialog when the screen is off. Also allow back to make the progress dialog go away.
Make the timeout a final variable. Also make sure to broadcast a fail in the case when a second login attempt gets called before the first one is done.

Overhaul the connection management to make it more reliable.
Merge AlarmReceiver into BackgroundManager as they have the same functionality: receive intents behind your back. No need to have 2 things with the same function. Login ALWAYS runs in "async mode". NEVER EVER wait for a result from login because it will stall the ui thread and cause the app to die. Use different callback modes for login for whether a foreground (ui screen) or BackgroundManager called the login so the result can be sent to the appropriate place. Remove convoluted 3 tiered approach to relogging in. Don't know if it really is useful but adds too many moving parts. Remove Vars.hasInternet because there is now Utils.hasInternet() which can check on the spot. It probably is faster performance to cache the result in Vars.hasInternet but adds another moving part and another thing that can go wrong. Remove Vars.cmdListenerRunning and Vars.dontRestart. These old strategies haven't been used in a while and are just rotting.

Don't allow the encoder/decoder threads to be started twice. When receiving a call and choosing to accept it (in CallMain.java) wait for the server to give the call start before moving to CallMain.java. Otherwise if the screen changes first and then call start is received, the threads will be started twice. The opposite is also true: if the call start is received in between the screen changes, CallMain will never switch into call mode. Starting the encoding thread twice will fail on creating the second AudioRecord and trigger a socket kill which will end the call.
Also, move AudioTrack and AudioRecord into their respective threads so they can be closed properly since they won't disappear with the ui.
Change compile date to git commit hash.
Reduce log spam of hasInternet which is espcially annoying in dblogs ui.

Reduce log spam. Adjust login retries to use a single use alarm. No point of a repeating alarm since you need to check after the login alarm fires whether it's needed or not. Instead of always cancelling and resetting, just set it once and reschedule if needed. Also make login retry work in background manager (prevously never did any scheduling)

Reduce log spam... again (for db logs ui)
Many cases where 1 function is producing 3+ logcat entries. Collect all messages and do a logcat at the end. Separate each message with a new line. Also too many broadcasts with a logcat sending and another when it is received. Don't need the same thing twice.
Small tweak for determining when to send the heartbeat. Check call status first before doing hasInternet function. Don't waste effort doing hasInternet if call status can tell you faster.
Add noise reduction and echo cancel toggle buttons. Disabled when in call ringing. Cannot be disabled once enabled (how android works). Turns red if cell phone can't do, green if it can.

Handle the case when: -you're looking at user home but the login is taking a while because the connection is bad -you look at something else out of boredom -login sends a fail to broadcast_login_fg but nobody gets it because the app is in the background -it never retires until the connection dies and then comes back (hasInternet and android connectivity will start it by conincidence)
Always send the result to BackgroundManager so it can properly manage your login to the server and retry when needed. Rebroadcast the result as broadcast_login_fg so the ui can do its thing with the result too. If there is no ui waiting for it, no harm. (Not worth adding some extra moving parts for "should rebroadcast" or "broadcast mode" or some other mode switch in login async)
Put back missing log cat of when background manager receives login broadcast.
